# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: small-multiples
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:small-multiples/data-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:small-multiples/faceting] In geometry, **faceting** (also spelled **facetting**) is the process of removing parts of a polygon, polyhedron or polytope, without creating any new vertices.
[src:small-multiples/faceting] New edges of a faceted polyhedron may be created along face diagonals or internal space diagonals.
[src:small-multiples/faceting] A *faceted polyhedron* will have two faces on each edge and creates new polyhedra or compounds of polyhedra.
[src:small-multiples/faceting] Faceting is the reciprocal or dual process to *stellation*.
[src:small-multiples/faceting] For every stellation of some convex polytope, there exists a dual faceting of the dual polytope.
[src:small-multiples/faceting] For example, a regular pentagon has one symmetry faceting, the pentagram, and the regular hexagon has two symmetric facetings, one as a polygon, and one as a compound of two triangles.
[src:small-multiples/faceting] The regular icosahedron can be faceted into three regular Kepler–Poinsot polyhedra: small stellated dodecahedron, great dodecahedron, and great icosahedron.
[src:small-multiples/faceting] The regular dodecahedron can be faceted into one regular Kepler–Poinsot polyhedron, three uniform star polyhedra, and three regular polyhedral compound.
[src:small-multiples/faceting] The uniform stars and compound of five cubes are constructed by face diagonals.
[src:small-multiples/faceting] The excavated dodecahedron is a facetting with star hexagon faces.
[src:small-multiples/faceting] The stella octangula is the sole faceting of the cube, and the tetrahedron has no facetings.
[src:small-multiples/faceting] Faceting has not been studied as extensively as stellation.
[src:small-multiples/small-multiple] A **small multiple** (sometimes called **trellis chart**, **lattice chart**, **grid chart**, or **panel chart**) is a series of similar graphs or charts using the same scale and axes, allowing them to be easily compared.
[src:small-multiples/small-multiple] It uses multiple views to show different partitions of a dataset.
[src:small-multiples/small-multiple] The term was popularized by Edward Tufte.
[src:small-multiples/small-multiple] In the example, the departmental salary expense is charted by month with a dashed line indicating the average for each department.
[src:small-multiples/small-multiple] The scales on each panel are different to emphasize the relative change over time compared to the range.
[src:small-multiples/small-multiple] Standardizing the scales could provide insight into comparisons in magnitude between the different departments.
[src:small-multiples/small-multiple] Two independent Y axes may be utilized when presenting data with different numeric scales in each panel.
[src:small-multiples/small-multiple] Muybridge's work not only proved for the first time that all four of a horse's hooves left the ground during gallop (see upper central plates), but it also broke new ground in terms of artistic expression and became foundational to the development of the motion picture.
[src:small-multiples/small-multiple] Muybridge went on to produce many more examples of small multiples showing animal locomotion through the medium of stop-motion photography, including boys playing leapfrog and a bison cantering.
[src:small-multiples/small-multiple] Adjacent is a chart showing the population broken down by occupation, including a count of those attending school, according to the 1870 Census.
[src:small-multiples/small-multiple] This graphic is innovative in its use of both a treemap display and a latticed layout of small multiples.
[src:small-multiples/small-multiple] Additional examples appearing in the *Atlas* include side-by-side geographic maps showing the changes in population over time, as well as tiled mosaic charts showing population demographic breakdowns, and diverging bar graphs showing deaths broken down by age and gender, tiled by state.
[src:small-multiples/small-multiple] Small multiples are a popular technique in cartographic design for multivariate mapping.
[src:small-multiples/small-multiple] As with the small multiple chart, each panel uses the same underlying two-dimensional space, but in this case that is a geographic space.
[src:small-multiples/small-multiple] Typically, the variables being mapped are of a similar type, such as types of agricultural products, so that the same strategy of map symbol can be used on each panel, enabling rapid comparison between the maps.
[src:small-multiples/small-multiple] Another common use of small multiples is to show change in spatial patterns over time, as an alternative to an animated map.
[src:small-multiples/small-multiple] Several tests of the effectiveness of each method have generally concluded that they have distinct advantages, with animation being better for seeing trends, especially movement, and small multiples being better for making comparisons between times.
[src:small-multiples/statistical-graphics] Whereas statistics and data analysis procedures generally yield their output in numeric or tabular form, graphical techniques allow such results to be displayed in some sort of pictorial form.
[src:small-multiples/statistical-graphics] They include plots such as scatter plots, histograms, probability plots, spaghetti plots, residual plots, box plots, block plots and biplots.
[src:small-multiples/statistical-graphics] Exploratory data analysis (EDA) relies heavily on such techniques.
[src:small-multiples/statistical-graphics] They can also provide insight into a data set to help with testing assumptions, model selection and regression model validation, estimator selection, relationship identification, factor effect determination, and outlier detection.
[src:small-multiples/statistical-graphics] In addition, the choice of appropriate statistical graphics can provide a convincing means of communicating the underlying message that is present in the data to others.
[src:small-multiples/statistical-graphics] If one is not using statistical graphics, then one is forfeiting insight into one or more aspects of the underlying structure of the data.
[src:small-multiples/statistical-graphics] Statistical graphics have been central to the development of science and date to the earliest attempts to analyse data.
[src:small-multiples/statistical-graphics] Many familiar forms, including bivariate plots, statistical maps, bar charts, and coordinate paper were used in the 18th century.
[src:small-multiples/statistical-graphics] Since the 1970s statistical graphics have been re-emerging as an important analytic tool with the revitalisation of computer graphics and related technologies.
[src:small-multiples/statistical-graphics] See the plots page for many more examples of statistical graphics.
[src:small-multiples/trellis-graph] A **trellis** is a graph whose nodes are ordered into vertical slices (*time*) with every node at almost every time connected to at least one node at an earlier and at least one node at a later time.
[src:small-multiples/trellis-graph] The earliest and latest times in the trellis have only one node (hence the "almost" in the preceding sentence).
[src:small-multiples/trellis-graph] Trellises are used in encoders and decoders for communication theory and encryption.
[src:small-multiples/trellis-graph] They are also the central datatype used in Baum–Welch algorithm or the Viterbi Algorithm for Hidden Markov Models.
[src:small-multiples/trellis-graph] The trellis graph is named for its similar appearance to an architectural trellis.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] A **visual variable**, in cartographic design, graphic design, and data visualization, is an aspect of a graphical object that can visually differentiate it from other objects, and can be controlled during the design process.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Graphic techniques have been used in maps and statistical charts to represent non-visual information since the 17th Century, and information visualization blossomed in the 19th Century, highlighted by the work of William Playfair and Charles Joseph Minard.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] However, the direct study of this abstract use of graphical appearance began with the emergence of cartography as an academic research discipline in the mid-20th Century.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] In *The Look of Maps* (1952), often considered the genesis of American cartographic theory, Arthur H.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Robinson discussed the role of size, shape, and color in establishing contrast in maps.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] At the same time in France, Jacques Bertin published an early version of his list of visual variables: shape, value, and "sparkling" (grain).
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Robinson, in his 1960 *Elements of Cartography*, which quickly became the dominant textbook on the subject, discussed size, shape, color, and pattern as the qualities of map symbols that establish contrast and represent geographic information.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Bertin was a cartographer at the École pratique des hautes études (EPHE) in Paris, where he created maps and graphics for faculty from various disciplines using a wide variety of data.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Despite having a background in cartography, and deriving many of his ideas by evaluating maps, he intended for *Sémiologie Graphique* to be applied to all forms of graphic design and information visualization.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Soon the idea was gaining international acceptance; in 1974 Joel Morrison presented a very similar system in the context of cartographic generalization, citing neither Bertin nor Robinson but saying that it was a "traditional categorization," suggesting its widespread nature by that point.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Despite the title of Bertin's work, it actually contained little reference to the scientific knowledge in the field of Semiotics or any other, and was primarily a practical summation of patterns he found in practice.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] The "truth" of the visual variables concept was largely established by its widespread and long-lasting acceptance.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] The earliest lists commonly suggested six variables: location size, shape, value, hue, orientation, and grain (pattern spacing).
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] To this list, several additions have been suggested, with a few entering the canonical lists found in textbooks, while other suggestions have largely been dropped in cartography.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] With the rise of multimedia as a cartographic tool, analogous sets of non-visual communication variables have also been presented.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Starting with Robinson and Bertin, a core set of visual variables has become largely canonical, appearing in cartography and information visualization textbooks, and built into most design software in some form.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] The size of a symbol is how much space it occupies.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] This commonly refers to the area of point symbols, and the thickness of line symbols.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Size differences are relatively easy to recognize, making it a useful variable to convey information, such as a quantitative amount of something, or relative importance.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Studies have shown that humans are better at judging relative differences in linear distance (e.g. one road being twice as thick as another) than relative differences in area (e.g., one circle having twice the area of another).
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Such estimations are the most accurate from squares.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Area differences of circles are generally underestimated, but there is a large variation between people in ability to estimate two-dimensional size.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Correctly estimating relative volume has proven even more difficult.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Because geographical features have an actual size on the Earth, this cannot always be controlled, and sometimes works against the wishes of a cartographer; for example, it can be difficult to make a world map in which Russia does not stand out.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] In a cartogram the size of features is purposefully distorted to represent a variable other than area.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] A shape is a simple design that is used to symbolize an attribute on a map.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Shape is most commonly attached to point features in maps.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Some shapes are simple in nature and thus are more abstract, while other shapes are more pictorial and are easy for the reader to comprehend what is trying to be conveyed.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Some aspects of shape are inherent to the phenomenon and may not be easily manipulable, especially in line and region symbols, such as the shape of a road or a country.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] However, shape can still play a role in line and region symbols, such as a region filled with tree symbols or an arrowhead on a line.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Also, the shape of a feature may be purposefully distorted by Cartographic generalization, especially when creating schematic representations such as many transit maps, although this distortion is rarely used to convey information, only to reduce emphasis on shape and location.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] As an aspect of color, **value** refers to how light or dark an object appears.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Value effectively connotes "more" and "less," an ordinal measure; this makes it a very useful form of symbology in thematic maps, especially choropleth maps.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Value contributes strongly to Visual hierarchy; elements that contrast most with the value of the background tend to stand out most (e.g., black on a white sheet of paper, white on a black computer screen).
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] The **saturation** of a color is its purity or intensity, created by the variety of light composing it; a single wavelength of light is of the highest saturation, while white, black, or gray has no saturation (being an even mixture of all visible wavelengths).
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Of the three psychological aspects of color, this is the least effective at conveying specific information, but it is very effective at establishing figure-ground and visual hierarchy, with bright colors generally standing out more than muted tones or shades of gray.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Bertin mentions saturation in his discussion of "color" (hue), but did not include it as a distinct variable.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Orientation refers to the direction labels and symbols are facing on a map (occasionally called "direction" or "angle").
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Although it is not used as often as many of the other visual variables, it can be useful for communicating information about the real-world orientation of features.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Common examples include wind direction and the direction in which a spring flows.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Although terminology for this aspect still varies somewhat today, *texture* or *pattern* in this context generally refers to an aggregate symbol composed of recurring sub-symbols.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] This can include areas (such as a forest filled with small tree point symbols) and line symbols (such as a railroad with recurring cross-hatches).
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] The amount of white space between the sub-symbols in the pattern.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Bertin's French term *grain* was translated as "texture" in the 1983 English edition, and appeared frequently as such in subsequent lists, but others have suggested that *granularity* or just *grain* is a better translation.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] The orderliness of the location of the sub-symbols in the pattern, generally either regularly spaced in rows and columns (often indicating a human construction, such as an orchard), or randomly spaced (often indicating a natural distribution).
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] A number of additional variables have been suggested at times.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Some are recent technology-driven proposals, while others are earlier entries that have fallen out of favor.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] The absolute location of the symbol in the design, specified as (x,y) coordinates.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] This was a core part of Bertin's model, who distinguished these "imposition variables" from the other "retinal variables." This has largely been dropped from most subsequent lists by cartographers, since location in a map is predetermined by geography.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] However, it is crucial for representing information in charts and other data visualizations; for example, position is the main method of visualizing quantitative values in a scatterplot.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Even in cartography, position becomes a variable when labeling and laying out the non-map elements on the page.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] It is also relevant when representing fields; for example, the location of an isoline is an abstract visualization of a property, not the location of a real-world linear feature.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] In a regular arrangement, the direction in which the sub-symbols are arrayed.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Bertin considered this just the area version of the primary variable of orientation, but Morrison included it as a separate variable, likely because the orientation of the individual sub-symbols may be different than the angle in which they are arranged.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] In recent years, it has rarely been included, likely due to the overall decrease in the use of fill patterns in the era of digital cartography.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] These corollary terms refer to the degree to which a symbol blends with other symbols at the same location, giving the illusion of the symbol in front being translucent.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] A fairly recent addition, the control of opacity has become common in digital cartography.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] While it is rarely used to convey specific information, it is effective for reducing contrast or to retain underlying information.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Despite its widespread use, it is rarely mentioned in textbooks.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] This is the degree to which a symbol is drawn with crisp or fuzzy edges.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Briefly mentioned in the *Elements* textbook in 1978, the concept was more fully developed by Alan MacEachren in 1992 as a tool for representing locational uncertainty; he first called it *focus*, then chose *crispness*, which has been the most common term in subsequent lists.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] This is the technique of purposefully pixelating a symbol or feature as a way of generalizing and obscuring it, usually for communicating some form of uncertainty about the feature.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] This was also first introduced in that context by MacEachren, but is not commonly used, and has rarely been mentioned since.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] By extension, this can also refer to the general level of detail in a symbol, which is used more often than pixelation, especially in the context of cartographic generalization.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] On three-dimensional perspective maps, it is common to extrude shapes in the z direction, so that height represents a property.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] According to Bertin, each of the visual variables suggests its own mode of perception and interpretation, which MacEachren ties to the cognitive theory of Image schema (e.g., size: Large-small ~ more-less).
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] These modes make each variable better for representing certain kinds of information, and serving certain purposes, than others.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Specifically, Bertin introduces four properties of these variables, which tie them directly to their role in the visual hierarchy and to their ability to represent data in each of Steven's levels of measurement.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Each of these variables may be employed to convey information, to provide contrast between different features and layers, to establish figure-ground contrast and a clear visual hierarchy, or add to the aesthetic appeal of the map.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Map symbols commonly employ multiple visual variables simultaneously.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] This can be used to reinforce the depiction of a single property; for example, a capital city having a symbol that is larger and a different shape than other cities, or a color progression on a choropleth map from pale yellow to dark green, using both hue and value.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Alternatively, different visual variables may be used to represent different properties; for example, symbols for cities may be differentiated by size to indicate population, and by shape to indicate provincial and national capitals.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] Some visual variable can be combined harmoniously to make a map clearer and more informative, while other combinations tend to add more confusion than usefulness.
[src:small-multiples/visual-variable] For example, early experiments with using Chernoff faces on maps have been criticized as difficult to interpret correctly.
